{"Body":"<p>It is true that nasals (n, m, etc.) are the most frequent option for negation. And while there is an easy explanation for the words for \"mother\" (which also mostly use nasals, and which follows from the first sounds made by babies), it is not that clear for negation. <a href=\"http://books.google.com/books?id=c7LxaLP5xogC&amp;pg=PA193&amp;lpg=PA193&amp;dq=negation%20nasal%20languages&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=So_aRcbX0-&amp;sig=UhvVatCjPUP7dqc6dHDVJKjPV4U&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=XFBwTu6SKurg4QTKtdjBCQ&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;ct=result&amp;resnum=5&amp;sqi=2&amp;ved=0CDYQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&amp;q=negation%20nasal%20languages&amp;f=false\" rel=\"nofollow\">Here is a hypothesis</a>:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The use of nasal phonemes in the negative in so many languages of the world must in some way be related to to prevailingly nasal character of the grunt.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "Id":"82", "ParentId":"67", "LastEditorUserId":"80", "CreationDate":"2011-09-14T06:59:55.393", "OwnerUserId":"80", "PostTypeId":"2", "comments":[], "LastEditDate":"2011-09-14T13:26:17.510", "LastEditedUser":{"UpVotes":"14", "WebsiteUrl":"http://techblog.bozho.net", "Id":"80", "AccountId":"70258", "CreationDate":"2011-09-13T23:45:02.257", "AboutMe":"<p>Bozhidar Bozhanov - Senior Java developer (<a href=\"http://bozho.net/cv/Bozhidar_Bozhanov_CV.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">CV</a>)</p>\n\n<p>Creator of <a href=\"http://welshare.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://welshare.com</a></p>\n", "Age":"27", "Location":"Sofia, Bulgaria", "DownVotes":"0", "Views":"29", "Reputation":"753", "DisplayName":"Bozho", "LastAccessDate":"2012-08-08T11:21:15.973"}, "LastActivityDate":"2011-09-14T13:26:17.510", "Score":"2", "CommentCount":"4", "OwnerUser":{"UpVotes":"14", "WebsiteUrl":"http://techblog.bozho.net", "Id":"80", "AccountId":"70258", "CreationDate":"2011-09-13T23:45:02.257", "AboutMe":"<p>Bozhidar Bozhanov - Senior Java developer (<a href=\"http://bozho.net/cv/Bozhidar_Bozhanov_CV.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">CV</